Money has different buying power in the Twokinds world that makes it hard to be directly equivalent to our money, but a gold coin is essentially like a 100 dollar bill, I suppose.
300 gold coins is the average price of a small house.
Yes but it would have in 1900, in equivalent today's dollars. You have to remmeber that these aren't modern homes, with wiring, advanced materials or insulation.
That's why I say, it's hard to directly compare the dollar to the buying power.
Because our costs today have changed so much.
But essentially, for an average Twokinds citizen, a gold coin is a little more than 1 month of mortgage, factoring in a 30 year 300g home.
Not counting taxes and interest, of course.
I don't know. I imaigne, though, that's what a lot of people would do.
Looking at prices for houses in the Sears cataloge, some house kits could be bought for 600 dollars in 1908, which is the equivilent of $17,936 in today's money.
So, it would vary, but I imagine building it yourself would be something like 200 gold, + time.
Some luxery manors you could buy back then cost a whopping $8000!
Which would be 240,000 in today's money.
So that'd be like 2000 gold houses in the Twokinds world.
Oh, just a little bit more.
Trace's manor is definitely not a 2500g manor.
For the average person, who thinks 300g is a ton of money, it's an unthinkable amount.
I generally tried to make each gold piece hold a lot of value.

Copper is 1c. Silver is 100c. Gold is 1000c.

There's no words for the kind of ranks the tigers arranged themselves in.
Flora was captured by slavers, who were taking her to the capital to be sold as a slave to nobility, tigers being considered exotic.
But she escaped from the cart cages during the journey (when the caravan was attacked), and ended up falling into a river while on the run and washing up on a farm in Edinmire.
Where she was found by a white wolf named Euchre.
Euchre took her to the humans of the farm, who took her in. When the slaving company came looking for the escaped tiger, the farm family covered her up.
They grew to treat her as somewhat of a daughter, but the relationship grew increasingly strained as she got older and the realities of the class different became more present.
Flora eventually decided she had to leave the life behind and ran.
He worked as a voluntary indentured servant, which is something Keidran can do legally, though obviously it's rarely a good arrangement.
